# LM Uptime Export

This guide is for running `Export-LMUptimeCounts.ps1` without needing to know
the full LogicMonitor API details.

The script looks at your LogicMonitor LM Uptime checks, figures out how often
they run, and creates CSV files you can open in Excel or share with others.

## What You Need First

You need PowerShell and the official LogicMonitor PowerShell module.

Install the module once:

```powershell
Install-Module Logic.Monitor -Scope CurrentUser
```

You also need LogicMonitor API credentials. You can use either:

- LMv1 `AccessId` and `AccessKey`
- A bearer token
- A saved LogicMonitor credential
- An already-open `Connect-LMAccount` session

## Fastest Way To Run It

If you have LMv1 credentials:

```powershell
$env:LM_ACCESS_ID = "your-access-id"
$env:LM_ACCESS_KEY = "your-access-key"

.\Export-LMUptimeCounts.ps1 `
  -AccountName "your-portal-name" `
  -StartMonth 2026-01 `
  -EndMonth 2026-05 `
  -OutputDir .\exports\lm-uptime
```

Replace `your-portal-name` with the part before `.logicmonitor.com`.

For example, if your portal is:

```text
acme.logicmonitor.com
```

then use:

```powershell
-AccountName "acme"
```

## If You Use A Bearer Token

```powershell
$env:LM_BEARER_TOKEN = "your-bearer-token"

.\Export-LMUptimeCounts.ps1 `
  -AccountName "your-portal-name" `
  -BearerToken $env:LM_BEARER_TOKEN `
  -StartMonth 2026-05 `
  -EndMonth 2026-05 `
  -OutputDir .\exports\lm-uptime
```

## What The Script Creates

The script creates CSV files by default.

The most useful files are:

- `monthly_uptime_test_counts.csv`
  Shows each LM Uptime check and how many tests it ran per month.

- `monthly_uptime_totals.csv`
  Shows monthly totals across all checks.

- `uptime_devices.csv`
  Lists the LM Uptime devices found in the portal.

- `uptime_datasource_instances.csv`
  Lists the individual locations or instances used for counting.

- `uptime_warnings.csv`
  Lists anything the script had to guess or skip.

If you only need test counts, start with:

```text
monthly_uptime_test_counts.csv
monthly_uptime_totals.csv
```

## Estimated Counts vs Actual Counts

By default, the script uses estimated counts.

That means it calculates:

```text
how many times the check should run in the month
*
how many enabled locations or instances it has
```

This is fast and usually what you want for reporting.

Run estimated mode like this:

```powershell
.\Export-LMUptimeCounts.ps1 `
  -AccountName "your-portal-name" `
  -BearerToken $env:LM_BEARER_TOKEN `
  -Mode Estimated `
  -StartMonth 2026-05 `
  -EndMonth 2026-05
```

Actual mode asks LogicMonitor for stored datapoints and counts what comes back.
It is slower and depends on how much data LogicMonitor still has retained.

Use actual mode only when you need to compare expected runs to returned data:

```powershell
.\Export-LMUptimeCounts.ps1 `
  -AccountName "your-portal-name" `
  -BearerToken $env:LM_BEARER_TOKEN `
  -Mode Both `
  -StartMonth 2026-05 `
  -EndMonth 2026-05
```

## Common Things You Might Want To Change

Only export web uptime checks:

```powershell
.\Export-LMUptimeCounts.ps1 `
  -AccountName "your-portal-name" `
  -BearerToken $env:LM_BEARER_TOKEN `
  -Type uptimewebcheck
```

Only export ping uptime checks:

```powershell
.\Export-LMUptimeCounts.ps1 `
  -AccountName "your-portal-name" `
  -BearerToken $env:LM_BEARER_TOKEN `
  -Type uptimepingcheck
```

Only export internal checks:

```powershell
.\Export-LMUptimeCounts.ps1 `
  -AccountName "your-portal-name" `
  -BearerToken $env:LM_BEARER_TOKEN `
  -IsInternal $true
```

Only export external checks:

```powershell
.\Export-LMUptimeCounts.ps1 `
  -AccountName "your-portal-name" `
  -BearerToken $env:LM_BEARER_TOKEN `
  -IsInternal $false
```

Write JSON files too:

```powershell
.\Export-LMUptimeCounts.ps1 `
  -AccountName "your-portal-name" `
  -BearerToken $env:LM_BEARER_TOKEN `
  -OutputFormat Both
```

## If The Counts Look Wrong

Open `uptime_warnings.csv` first.

The most common reason is that the script could not find a polling interval on
one or more devices. When that happens, it uses `5` minutes as the default.

You can change the fallback:

```powershell
.\Export-LMUptimeCounts.ps1 `
  -AccountName "your-portal-name" `
  -BearerToken $env:LM_BEARER_TOKEN `
  -DefaultIntervalMinutes 10
```

If your portal stores the polling interval in a custom property, tell the
script the property name:

```powershell
.\Export-LMUptimeCounts.ps1 `
  -AccountName "your-portal-name" `
  -BearerToken $env:LM_BEARER_TOKEN `
  -PollingIntervalProperties @("my.custom.interval", "pollingInterval")
```

## If The Script Does Not Run

If PowerShell says scripts are blocked:

```powershell
Set-ExecutionPolicy -Scope CurrentUser RemoteSigned
```

If the LogicMonitor commands are not found:

```powershell
Install-Module Logic.Monitor -Scope CurrentUser
Import-Module Logic.Monitor
```

If authentication fails, confirm:

- Your portal name is only the subdomain, not the full URL.
- Your API credential has read permissions.
- Your token or access key has not expired or been rotated.

## Quick Sanity Check

Before running a big report, test one month first:

```powershell
.\Export-LMUptimeCounts.ps1 `
  -AccountName "your-portal-name" `
  -BearerToken $env:LM_BEARER_TOKEN `
  -StartMonth 2026-05 `
  -EndMonth 2026-05 `
  -OutputDir .\exports\lm-uptime-test
```

Then open:

```text
.\exports\lm-uptime-test\monthly_uptime_totals.csv
```

If the totals look reasonable, run the wider date range.
